Your issue happens because you are setting the session before checking verification.
So when an unverified user tries to login, this line already runs:

Session::put('user_id',$user->id);
session(['role'=>'user']);

Because of this, the system thinks a user is already logged in, so when you try to login as admin, it blocks it.

Correct Logic (Fix)

You must check verification first, then create session and login.

Correct checkLogin() code
public function checkLogin(Request $request)
{
    // prevent admin already logged
    if(session('role') == 'admin'){
        return back()->with('error','Admin already logged in. Logout first.');
    }

    $user = User::where('email',$request->email)->first();

    if(!$user || !Hash::check($request->password,$user->password)){
        return back()->with('error','Invalid credentials');
    }

    // CHECK VERIFIED FIRST
    if ($user->status != 'verified') {
        return back()->with('error', 'Wait for admin verification');
    }

    // THEN LOGIN
    Auth::login($user);

    Session::put('user_id',$user->id);
    session(['role'=>'user']);

    return redirect('/home');
}
 Why this Fix Works

Before fix:

Unverified user login
↓
Session created
↓
System thinks user logged in
↓
Admin login blocked

After fix:

Unverified user login
↓
Verification check fails
↓
NO SESSION CREATED
↓
Admin can login normally
Also Small Issue in Middleware

You used Auth but didn't import it.

Add this at top of CheckVerified.php

use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;
 Best Status Practice (Important)

Instead of string 'verified', better use numbers:

0 = unverified
1 = verified
2 = inactive

Then check like:

if ($user->status != 1) {
    return back()->with('error','Wait for admin verification');
}

More professional and faster.

